1 Introduction

This document presents an exploratory graphical analysis of the âSurvival from Malignant Melanomaâ data setwhich is available on Canvas. The data consists of measurements made on patients with malignant melanoma. Each patient had their tumor removed by surgery at the Department of Plastic Surgery, University Hospital of Odense, Denmark during the period 1962 to 1977. The surgery consisted of complete removal of the tumor together with about 2.5cm of the surrounding skin.

1.1 The 1977 Maligant Melanoma DataSet

Among the measurements taken were the thickness of the tumor in âmmâ and whether it was ulcerated or not with which was represented with categorical variables 0 and 1 where 0 indicates the absence of ulceration and 1 indicates presence of ulcers on the tumors removed . These are thought to be important prognostic variables in that patients with a thick and/or ulcerated tumor have an increased chance of death from melanoma. Patients were followed until the end of 1977. The data also includes information on the âtime in daysâ since the operation and of the status of patients at the end of the study in 1977. â1 indicating that they had died from melanoma, 2 indicates that they were still alive and 3 indicates that they had died from causes unrelated to their melanoma.â The data also includes the sex of patients,1=male, 0=female, the age of patients in years at the time of the operation and year of operation were also recorded.

Code
view(melanoma_2_)
#remove missing values and Reassign Dataset

Code
#Visualise of time distribution
hist(melanoma_2$time, main = "Survival Time after Surgery", xlab = "Time after surgery in days", ylab = "Survival Probability")

The above histogram of theÂ TimeÂ variable visualizes the distribution of survival times among patients. The x-axis represents the survival time in days, and the y-axis represents the frequency of patients with that survival time. The histogram easily identifies a good proportion of patients lived for about 1500 to 2500 days after surgery.
